    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Courts often look for a distinction between a \"random act of God\" and an \"unforeseeable technical chaos\" by examining the nature of the event and the circumstances surrounding it. A lightning strike, for example, is often considered a random act of God, as it is an unpredictable and uncontrollable event. On the other hand, a complex, cascading failure in the grid architecture, while unpredictable, may be considered more of an unforeseeable technical chaos, as it is often the result of a combination of factors, including design flaws, inadequate maintenance, or unforeseen interactions between different systems.\n\nIn determining whether the event was truly outside the party's control, courts may also consider factors such as:\n\n* The likelihood of the event occurring: Was it a rare occurrence, or was it a predictable consequence of the supplier's actions or inactions?\n* The supplier's ability to anticipate and mitigate the risk: Did the supplier take reasonable measures to prevent or minimize the impact of the event?\n* The degree of control the supplier had over the event: Was the supplier able to influence the outcome of the event, or was it entirely outside of their control?\n\nUltimately, the distinction between a disaster and just bad luck or system instability can be blurry",
